awd_titl_txt: REU SITE: Interdisciplinary Micro/nano/additive-manufacturing Program Addressing Challenges Today - Next Generation (IMPACT-NG)
awd_abstract_narration:
This Research Experience for Undergraduates (REU) Program at the University of Louisville trains a diverse cohort of interdisciplinary STEM students in the field of Advanced Manufacturing, with a special emphasis on micro/nano-manufacturing and additive manufacturing (i.e. 3D printing). As described in the recent 2018 Strategy for American Leadership in Advanced Manufacturing Report to the President of the United States, “America’s global economic dominance in the 20th century was primarily due to our nation’s creative advances in manufacturing techniques and strategies. However, this century has seen dramatic changes with significant declines in U.S. manufacturing productivity starting in the 1990s and accelerating losses during the 2008 recession”. The report further emphasizes the need to reverse that trend by encouraging programs that educate and train our next generation of workers about new manufacturing technologies and strategies. This REU program does exactly that through structured hands-on micro/nano/additive training classes, personalized independent research projects, professional faculty mentorship, student professional development, and exposure to a wide variety of applications in the fields of health, medicine, defense, security, energy, wearables, and manufacturing. 

The two most disruptive technologies in the field of Advanced Manufacturing are micro/nano-manufacturing and additive manufacturing (i.e. 3D printing). Furthermore, with recent material and resolution advances in 3D printing, we are experiencing the convergence of the two technologies, which promises to open up a completely new set of applications and range of products never before thought possible. The IMPACT-NG REU program at the University of Louisville sits squarely in that interesting space.  It addresses the national need to train the next generation of students about these converging technologies by formally educating them through intense hands-on laboratory experiences, followed by nine supervised weeks of personalized independent research involving an interesting interdisciplinary set of Advanced Manufacturing projects in the fields of health, medicine, defense, security, energy, wearables, and manufacturing. Projects range from diagnostic lab-on-a chip devices for the human health to advanced autonomous micro-robots for the environment to next-generation wearables for the Internet of Things. Finally, our program supplements their technical experiences with programs to improve their oral/written communication skills, opportunities to learn about graduate school, seminars about entrepreneurship, lunch meetings with technical and government leaders, tours of industry manufacturing facilities, ethics training, and a wide variety of organized social activities.

This award reflects NSF's statutory mission and has been deemed worthy of support through evaluation using the Foundation's intellectual merit and broader impacts review criteria.

por.por_cntn:
Intellectual Merit: The UofL IMPACT GEN 2 REU program successfully trained a diverse set of 28 undergraduate students in the converging Advanced Manufacturing fields of micro/nano technology and additive manufacturing (i.e. 3D printing).  Through various individualized research projects, the cohort collectively learned how these amazing next-generation "maker" technologies can be used to address challenges in the areas of robotics, energy, healthcare/medicine, manufacturing, bio-inspired products, the Internet of Things (IoT), and climate change. Our nation's global effectiveness and leadership in Advanced Manufacturing hinges on our ability to introduce the next generation of promising undergraduates to these powerful enabling technologies early in their academic careers. Hands-on educational programs like this intense REU are central to engaging more students early in their college experience from a wide range of disciplines, including Physics, Chemistry, Biology, ECE, ME, BE, ChE, CSE, Material Science, and even Art. 

Broader Impacts: This 10-week program trained a diverse set of undergraduate students about micro/nano/additive Advanced Manufacturing and illustrated how these cutting-edge technologies are used to solve a wide variety of technical and societal challenges. Our program emphasized hands-on training and research projects which reinforced our participants' learning experiences. Since micro/nano/additive manufacturing is a fundamental enabling technology, our program appealed to students from a wide range of disciplines (ECE, ME, ChE, BE, IE, Material Science, Chemistry, Physics, and Biology). Of the 9 REU students we recruited each year, ~1/3 were from the economically-depressed EPSCoR state of Kentucky, and ~2/3 from outside the Commonwealth. The intermingling of "Kentucky" students with "National" students provided several benefits. The "Kentucky" students helped the "National" students socialize and take advantage of unique regional offerings; and the "National" students inspired our in-state students to expand their horizons beyond the state and broaden their perspectives and goals. In addition, recruiting ~1/3 of our cohort from Kentucky helped improve our state's poor national standing in education, as Kentucky sadly ranks 47th in HS degrees at 81.7%, 47th in UG degrees at 21.0%, and 32nd in grad degrees at 8.5%. Since our Kentucky Feeder Schools consisted of HBCUs, community colleges, and colleges with limited or no research capabilities, our REU program also provided these students with a rare opportunity to engage in research and nurture their interests in STEM graduate opportunities. All our students were required to participate in 3 conferences/symposia during our 10-week program. This unique aspect of our program developed and improved our students' communication and presentation skills, which are often perceived shortcomings of future engineers and scientists. Through these 3 public activities, our students presented their research to over 500 people, impacting a large and broad audience. With our original IMPACT GEN 1 program, we developed a website which we have now been adding to for 6 years.  Our popular website contains a large amount of content about micro/nano/additive manufacturing including student-generated content such as technical reports and conference Power Points. All this information is available to the public, thus reaching a very broad and large national audience.

Outcomes Summary: The UofL IMPACT GEN 2 REU program hosted and supported 28 students from 2021 through 2023. Our 3 cohorts had very impressive outcomes. For example, the group produced 84 poster presentations and 32 oral talks at conferences, 1 journal publications in print, 4 conference papers, and 1 patent-pending. Several won impressive "best poster awards" at conferences where they competed against their graduate peers. In addition to their individual research project successes, our students participated in many Professional Development activities, such as lectures, technical workshops, safety-training sessions, our popular "Lunch-and-Learn" seminar series, and our unique hands-on micro/nano/additive training workshops. Our REU program grew in popularity. In Year 1 of our IMPACT Gen 2 program, our acceptance rate was 16% (56 applications received), and in Year 3, our acceptance rate was only 6% (140 applications received!).  These data demonstrate the popularity of both our REU program and its interdisciplinary advanced manufacturing theme. We are especially proud of our diversity-related demographics, in which our overall cohorts was 46% female, 25% traditional URMs (African American, Hispanic, or Native American), and 21% first-generation college students. Furthermore, including female students as underrepresented populations in engineering, the makeup of our 3-year REU cohorts was 67% underrepresented groups in Engineering! As our program gained in popularity over the years, the pool of applicants became more and more diverse, and our ability to admit more URM and female students increased! To date we can report a 100% college retention rate for all our REU participants.  From our cohort of 2021, 10% finished their MS degrees, 10% are enrolled in grad school, and 100% finished their BS degrees. Our 2022 and 2023 cohorts are still working on their BS degrees. Aside from post-program surveys, we also use LinkedIn to remain in contact with our REU graduates and monitor their careers and career achievements.
